    <section class="container section-pad pillar">
      <h2>Complete Guide to Home EV Charging in West Michigan</h2>
      <p>
        Installing a Level 2 EV charger at home is the single biggest quality-of-life upgrade an EV owner makes: the car
        charges while you sleep on cheap overnight rates, you never queue at public chargers, and your daily routine
        never depends on a third party's infrastructure. The install itself is straightforward — a dedicated 240V
        circuit and a wall-mount charger — but the decisions around charger type, panel capacity, location, and rebates
        determine the final cost for your specific scope.
      </p>
      <p>This guide walks through the full decision tree for a Holland, Grand Rapids, or West Michigan EV install.</p>

      <h3>Level 1 vs Level 2: Pick the Right Charger First</h3>
      <p>
        Level 1 uses the standard 120V cord that came with your car. It adds 3–5 miles of range per hour. Level 2 uses a
        dedicated 240V circuit and adds 20–40 miles per hour. For commutes under 30 miles a day with overnight parking,
        Level 1 is enough. For commutes over 40 miles, two-EV households, or any larger battery vehicle (Lightning,
        Cybertruck, Rivian), Level 2 is the right call.
      </p>
      <p>
        See <a href="/blog/level-1-vs-level-2-ev-charger">Level 1 vs Level 2 EV charger: which should you install?</a>
        for the full comparison, hardware recommendations, and the difference between plug-in (NEMA 14-50) and hardwired
        installs.
      </p>

      <h3>Does Your Panel Support It?</h3>
      <p>
        A Level 2 charger draws 16–48 amps continuous. On a 100-amp service home already running central AC, electric
        range, and electric dryer, that's often too much without a panel upgrade. The decision follows a documented
        <a href="/glossary/load-calculation">NEC Article 220 load calculation</a> — not a guess.
      </p>
      <p>
        See <a href="/blog/do-i-need-a-panel-upgrade-for-an-ev-charger">do I need a panel upgrade for an EV charger?</a>
        for the decision criteria. If you do need a panel upgrade,
        <a href="/blog/100-amp-vs-200-amp-panel">100 amp vs 200 amp panel: which does your home need?</a> covers the sizing
        math, and <a href="/panel-upgrades">our panel-upgrade service</a> covers what that work involves.
      </p>

      <h3>Where to Put the Charger</h3>
      <p>
        Charger location seems trivial until you've lived with one. The wrong wall means dragging a 30-pound cable
        across the garage every night. The right wall makes plugging in as automatic as parking.
      </p>
      <p>
        Key decisions: which wall (matches your car's charge port location), mount height (48 inches is standard), cable
        length (20–25 ft is the sweet spot), and panel-to-charger run length (the biggest install-cost driver). See
        <a href="/blog/where-to-install-ev-charger">where to install your EV charger: garage layout tips</a>.
      </p>

      <h3>Rebates: What Michigan Pays For</h3>
      <p>
        Both Consumers Energy and DTE Energy run residential EV charger rebate programs. Each pays up to $500 for
        installing a qualified networked Level 2 charger, plus enrollment in a discounted overnight EV rate. The federal
        Section 30C credit adds another 30% of installation cost (up to $1,000) for chargers in eligible census tracts —
        most of West Michigan qualifies.
      </p>
      <p>
        Stacking utility + federal rebates can meaningfully reduce your net out-of-pocket cost. See
        <a href="/blog/michigan-ev-charger-rebates">Michigan EV charger rebates & utility programs (2026)</a> for the current
        programs, eligibility, and the documentation we hand over at job close.
      </p>

      <h3>The Install Itself</h3>
      <p>A typical Level 2 install in West Michigan runs 4–6 hours and includes:</p>
      <ol>
        <li>Panel evaluation and load calculation.</li>
        <li>New 40 or 50 amp double-pole breaker.</li>
        <li>6 AWG copper feed from panel to charger location.</li>
        <li>NEMA 14-50 outlet (plug-in) or hardwired connection (allows full 48A continuous).</li>
        <li>Charger mounting and commissioning.</li>
        <li>Permit and inspection.</li>
      </ol>
      <p>
        Installs that include panel upgrades or runs to detached garages take longer and cost more. We quote both
        scenarios clearly during the site visit.
      </p>

      <h3>Outage Backup: Charging Through a Power Outage</h3>
      <p>
        A whole-home generator can run a Level 2 charger at reduced amperage during outages, provided the panel includes
        a smart load manager that sheds non-essential loads when generator capacity is approached. See
        <a href="/blog/automatic-transfer-switch-explained">what an automatic transfer switch does</a> for the technical
        detail, and <a href="/blog/how-to-size-a-whole-home-generator">how to size a whole-home generator</a>
        if you're planning both upgrades together.
      </p>

      <h3>West Michigan Specifics</h3>
      <p>
        Holland, Hudsonville, Grand Rapids, and the surrounding cities have well-established permit and inspection
        processes for EV charger installs. Holland Board of Public Works customers benefit from BPW's grid stability and
        lower rates but don't get the Consumers Energy rebate (separate utility). Lakeshore homes with detached garages
        often have trenching cost as the dominant variable. We map all of this during the walkthrough so the quote
        reflects the real scope.
      </p>
